{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1731eac2-d5cf-422b-b2c7-e628fab022c6","content":"Here's how to connect the **MCP Inspector** to your C# stdio MCP server:\n\n### 1. Launch the Inspector\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\n\nThis opens a web UI (usually at `http://localhost:6274`).\n\n### 2. Configure the connection\n\nIn the Inspector UI:\n\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `run --project /path/to/YourMcpServer.csproj`\n\nOr if you have a built DLL:\n\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `/path/to/YourMcpServer.dll`\n\nThen click **Connect**.\n\n### 3. Debug\n\nOnce connected, you can:\n\n- **Tools tab** — list, inspect, and invoke your tools with test inputs\n- **Resources tab** — browse exposed resources\n- **Notifications** — see server log messages in real time\n\n### Tips\n\n- **Environment variables:** Add any your server needs via the Inspector's env var fields before connecting.\n- **Logging:** Write diagnostic output to `stderr` (not `stdout`) — stdout is the MCP JSON-RPC channel. Use `Console.Error.WriteLine()` in C#.\n- **Breakpoints:** Attach a debugger to the `dotnet` process the Inspector spawns (find the PID via `ps aux | grep dotnet`), or add `Debugger.Launch()` in your code if on Windows.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b1e802c2-9a00-492a-a9ea-a30dca5ee10c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug a C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question - I don't need to explore any codebase. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":417,"requestId":"5C3D:1EBB0A:1BDDCD8:1EFFC8E:69FA937B"},"id":"ede06436-bc3b-4d7b-b438-cbb19cbc6069","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:04:09.865Z","parentId":"a9b94c64-7a1f-4437-901e-b7457d81456e"}
